<subSubSection id="9C8860A05911A638FF0AC0A28360FBA5" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" type="nomenclature">
<paragraph id="D42D332B5911A638FF0AC0A28587FC15" blockId="2.[166,745,911,938]" box="[166,745,911,938]" pageId="2" pageNumber="389">
<heading id="8F6584475911A638FF0AC0A28587FC15" box="[166,745,911,938]" fontSize="36" level="2" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" reason="3">
<taxonomicName id="139248A85911A638FF0AC0A285FAFC15" authority="(Ehrenberg, 1838)" baseAuthorityName="Ehrenberg" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[166,660,911,938]" class="Lobosa" family="Thecamoebidae" genus="Thecamoeba" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Amoebida" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" phylum="Amoebozoa" rank="species" species="verrucosa">
<emphasis id="E6E6EF395911A638FF0AC0A286D7FC15" bold="true" box="[166,441,911,938]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="389">Thecamoeba verrucosa</emphasis>
(Ehrenberg, 1838)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="4CA92FAE5911A638FD0FC0A285B1FC15" box="[675,735,911,938]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="3.[174,207,469,491]" captionTargetBox="[264,1144,174,436]" captionTargetId="figure-281@3.[699,864,174,421]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="Fig. 3. Thecamoeba verrucosa, locomotory forms (a, b, c). x1240." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6502700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6502700/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="389">fig. 3</figureCitation>
)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D42D332B5911A638FF77C0928360FBA5" blockId="2.[166,1225,959,1242]" pageId="2" pageNumber="389">The species belongs to the rugose morphotype. Hyaloplasm forms numerous folds. Uroid is visible in the narrowed end of the amoeba body. Cell length is 150–250 μm, width is 80–120 μm, L/B ratio is 1.5–2.3. Single nucleus is 10–18 μm in diameter.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="9C8860A05911A638FF77C732863EFB65" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D42D332B5911A638FF77C732853DFBC5" blockId="2.[166,1225,959,1242]" pageId="2" pageNumber="389">
Remarks: the species can be distinguished from other species by shape and proportions of the cell, also by two tightly adjacent nucleoli in the nucleus (
<bibRefCitation id="B0034EDA5911A638FC3BC71283ABFBE5" author="Smirnov, A. V. &amp; Goodkov, A. V." box="[919,1221,1087,1114]" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" pagination="5 - 11" refId="ref2766" refString="Smirnov, A. V., Goodkov, A. V. 1993. Paradermamoeba valamo gen. n., sp. n. (Gymnamoebia, Thecamoebidae) - freshwater amoeba from bottom soil. Zoologicheskii Zhurnal, 72 (2), 5 - 11 [In Russian]." type="journal article" year="1993">Smirnov, Goodkov, 1993</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B0034EDA5911A638FF0AC7728648FBC5" author="Page, F. C." box="[166,294,1119,1146]" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" pagination="1 - 122" refId="ref2315" refString="Page, F. C. 1988. A new key to freshwater and soil gymnamoebae. Freshwater Biological Association. Ambleside, Cumbria, UK, 1 - 122." type="book chapter" year="1988">Page, 1988</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="B0034EDA5911A638FE9DC7728529FBC5" author="Page, F. C. &amp; Siemensma, F. J." box="[305,583,1119,1146]" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" pagination="3 - 170" refId="ref2346" refString="Page, F. C., Siemensma, F. J. 1991. Nackte Rhizopoda und Heliozoea (Protozoenfauna; Bd 2). Gustav Fischer Verlag, Stuttgart; New York, 3 - 170." type="book chapter" year="1991">Page, Siemensma, 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D42D332B5911A638FF77C75283A7FB25" blockId="2.[166,1225,959,1242]" box="[219,1225,1151,1178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="389">
Distribution: 
<taxonomicName id="139248A85911A638FED5C7AD8569FB26" baseAuthorityName="Ehrenberg" baseAuthorityYear="1838" box="[377,519,1152,1177]" class="Lobosa" family="Thecamoebidae" genus="Thecamoeba" kingdom="Protozoa" order="Amoebida" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" phylum="Amoebozoa" rank="species" species="verrucosa">
<emphasis id="E6E6EF395911A638FED5C7AD8569FB26" box="[377,519,1152,1177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="389">T. verrucosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in the most parts of Europe (
<bibRefCitation id="B0034EDA5911A638FC0BC75283D2FB25" author="Page, F. C. &amp; Siemensma, F. J." box="[935,1212,1151,1178]" pageId="2" pageNumber="389" pagination="3 - 170" refId="ref2346" refString="Page, F. C., Siemensma, F. J. 1991. Nackte Rhizopoda und Heliozoea (Protozoenfauna; Bd 2). Gustav Fischer Verlag, Stuttgart; New York, 3 - 170." type="book chapter" year="1991">Page, Siemensma, 1991</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
